<subSubSection lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="825" pageId="0" pageNumber="824" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="0.[685,1173,1310,1729]" pageId="0" pageNumber="824">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,814,1310,1331]" pageId="0" pageNumber="824">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body elongate-oval and of moderate size, length 4.0–6.0 mm; the elytra almost always with black maculae laterally and longitudinal band along the sutural line; elytral basal edge thickened and raised; labrum with sides subparallel; mandible with acute apex. Female pronotum with lateral sulci connected medially by an arcuate ridge. Male mesofemur with a fringe of long hairs along inner edge.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="0.[685,1173,1310,1729]" pageId="0" pageNumber="824">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1808" box="[709,969,1522,1543]" class="Insecta" family="Endomychidae" genus="Ancylopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="824" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melanocephalus">
<emphasis box="[709,969,1522,1543]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="824">Ancylopus melanocephalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from its congeners by a body length of 4.0–6.0 mm, mesotibia of male with inner margin slightly undulate and without a tooth, and the inner edge of the metatibia with minute serrations (
<figureCitation box="[1011,1105,1628,1650]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="1.[197,237,1129,1148]" captionTargetBox="[180,1182,189,1105]" captionTargetId="figure-245@1.[172,1194,183,1117]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs. 1–6. Ancylopus melanocephalus. 1) Male, habitus; 2) Female, habitus; 3) Aedeagus, dorsal view. 4) Aedeagus, lateral view; 5) Aedeagus, ventral view; 6) Abdomen and abdominal terminal segment, male." pageId="0" pageNumber="824">Figs. 1–6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="0.[685,1173,1310,1729]" lastBlockId="1.[173,659,1258,1466]" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="825" pageId="0" pageNumber="824">
The species most similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1808" box="[988,1171,1655,1676]" class="Insecta" family="Endomychidae" genus="Ancylopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="824" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melanocephalus">
<emphasis box="[988,1002,1655,1676]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="824">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1017,1171,1655,1676]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="824">melanocephalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is 
<taxonomicName authority="Strohecker, 1971" authorityName="Strohecker" authorityYear="1971" box="[710,1096,1681,1703]" class="Insecta" family="Endomychidae" genus="Ancylopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="824" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ceylonicus">
<emphasis box="[710,921,1681,1702]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="824">Ancylopus ceylonicus</emphasis>
Strohecker, 1971
</taxonomicName>
known from 
<collectingCountry box="[742,816,1708,1729]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="0" pageNumber="824">Ceylon</collectingCountry>
. Both species can be distinguished by the following key. Additionally, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Strohecker" authorityYear="1971" box="[529,659,1258,1280]" class="Insecta" family="Endomychidae" genus="Ancylopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="825" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ceylonicus">
<emphasis box="[529,543,1258,1279]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="825">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[558,659,1258,1279]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="825">ceylonicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished by the ferruginous color of the head, antennae, and legs and the black scutellum. The elytral suture, elytral apex, and elytral lateral margin are black, as well as a large, mediolateral elytral spot (
<figureCitation box="[455,534,1392,1413]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[175,215,1189,1208]" captionTargetBox="[151,637,194,1165]" captionTargetId="figure-272@2.[151,638,193,1177]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 7–9. Ancylopus ceylonicus. 7) Male, habitus, photograph by Floyd W. Shockley, Smithsonian Institution, Bugwood.org; 8) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 9) Mesotibia, male (from Strohecker 1971)." pageId="1" pageNumber="825">Figs. 7</figureCitation>
). The male genitalia are also different (compare 
<figureCitation box="[552,613,1418,1439]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="1.[197,237,1129,1148]" captionTargetBox="[180,1182,189,1105]" captionTargetId="figure-245@1.[172,1194,183,1117]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs. 1–6. Ancylopus melanocephalus. 1) Male, habitus; 2) Female, habitus; 3) Aedeagus, dorsal view. 4) Aedeagus, lateral view; 5) Aedeagus, ventral view; 6) Abdomen and abdominal terminal segment, male." pageId="1" pageNumber="825">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[173,234,1445,1466]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[175,215,1189,1208]" captionTargetBox="[151,637,194,1165]" captionTargetId="figure-272@2.[151,638,193,1177]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 7–9. Ancylopus ceylonicus. 7) Male, habitus, photograph by Floyd W. Shockley, Smithsonian Institution, Bugwood.org; 8) Aedeagus, dorsal view; 9) Mesotibia, male (from Strohecker 1971)." pageId="1" pageNumber="825">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
